elements.title: Mack AC
elements.contents: ... that Mack Trucks adopted the Bulldog as its corporate logo after World War I British soldiers nicknamed the Mack AC (example pictured) the "Bulldog", a reference to the model's tenacity and stub nose?

elements.title: Aaron Martin
elements.contents: ... that Aaron Martin missed his penalty kick in the longest penalty shoot-out in English professional football history?

elements.title: Polish proverbs
elements.contents: ... that there are tens of thousands of Polish proverbs, the oldest known of which dates to the year 1407?

elements.title: Concerto for Two Cellos, RV 531
elements.contents: ... that the Concerto for Two Cellos, RV 531, Antonio Vivaldi's only concerto for two cellos, begins unusually with the two soloists entering alone in fast imitation?

elements.title: Robert M. Briggs
elements.contents: ... that Robert M. Briggs won re-election to the Wisconsin State Assembly by promising Beetown a double-track railway that was "like two rows of brass buttons on a double-breasted vest"?

elements.title: Stuyvesant Farm
elements.contents: ... that when England moved to take over the Dutch colony of New Netherland in 1664, a delegation met at Stuyvesant Farm to negotiate the Articles of Surrender?

elements.title: Abraham O. Woodruff
elements.contents: ... that Abraham O. Woodruff married a second wife 11 years after his father, Wilford Woodruff, issued the 1890 Manifesto that banned the practice of plural marriage?

elements.title: Margaret Clemence
elements.contents: ... that Brookside character Margaret Clemence was featured in a female same-sex kiss that was rebroadcast during the opening ceremony of the 2012 Summer Olympics?
